// TEST: exec_iter_manual_drive
// EXPECT: output "sum=6"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python
//
// End-to-end proof that the embedded `core.iter` `ListIterator` drives the
// proven manual loop: `list_iter([1, 2, 3])` builds a `ListIterator[Int]`, and
// `loop { match it.next() { Some(x) => ...; None => break } }` sums its
// elements. This is the SAME drive shape as the hand-written
// `generic_iter_concrete_match.bock` (#149), here resolved through the embedded
// `core.iter` module.
//
// TARGETS — js/ts/python only (NOT rust/go). The embedded `core.iter` module
// compiles ALL its items into every importing program (no tree-shaking), so the
// generic combinator codegen residue on Rust and Go (FOUND in the PR: Rust
// `T: Clone` not propagated from the `next` impl to the combinator free
// functions; Go generic-record-construct emits `ListIterator[any]` in
// `list_iter` + `[]interface{}{x}` in concat-arg position + an `undefined: T`
// `Iterable` interface) fails the Rust/Go *compile* even for this manual-drive
// program that never calls a combinator. js/ts/python carry generics
// structurally and are unaffected. Restoring rust/go here is the codegen
// fast-follow tracked from this PR.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

use core.iter.{ListIterator, list_iter}

fn main() -> Void {
  let mut it: ListIterator[Int] = list_iter([1, 2, 3])
  let mut total: Int = 0
  loop {
    match it.next() {
      Some(x) => {
        total = total + x
      }
      None => break
    }
  }
  println("sum=${total}")
}
